data.content:
## .NET 8 Migration: `BackgroundProcessor`

### Critical Breaking Changes

1. **`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** in .NET 6+. It's completely removed.
2. **`ThreadAbortException` will never be thrown** — catching it is dead code.
3. **`Thread.ResetAbort()` also throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`**.

The modern replacement is **`CancellationToken`** with cooperative cancellation.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Task? _workerTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => ProcessLoop(token), token);
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking calls can unblock
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Cancellation requested — clean up partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break;
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        try
        {
            // Wait with a timeout instead of Thread.Sleep + Abort
            _workerTask?.Wait(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.All(e => e is OperationCanceledException))
        {
            // Expected on cancellation — swallow
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _workerTask?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **Blocking calls ignore cancellation** | If `GetNextItem()` blocks on I/O or `Monitor.Wait`, cancellation won't interrupt it. You **must** thread the `CancellationToken` into blocking calls (e.g., `BlockingCollection<T>.Take(token)`, `SemaphoreSlim.WaitAsync(token)`). |
| **`volatile bool` is insufficient** | The old `_running` flag can't unblock a thread stuck in a blocking call. `CancellationToken` can — via `token.Register()` or by passing it to APIs that accept it. |
| **`catch (ThreadAbortException)` was auto-rethrown** | In .NET Framework, `ThreadAbortException` rethrew at the end of `catch` unless `ResetAbort()` was called. `OperationCanceledException` does **not** auto-rethrow — you control flow normally. |
| **`Task` vs `Thread`** | `Task.Run` uses the thread pool, which is more efficient. If you need a dedicated long-running thread, use `Task.Factory.StartNew(..., TaskCreationOptions.LongRunning)`. |
| **Dispose the `CancellationTokenSource`** | `CTS` holds unmanaged resources (especially with `CancelAfter` or linked tokens). Always dispose it. |
| **`Wait()` can deadlock** | If called from a UI/sync-context thread, prefer `async Stop()` with `await _workerTask`. |

### If `GetNextItem()` Can't Accept a Token

Wrap it with a cancellation-aware helper:

```csharp
private async Task<Item> GetNextItemAsync(CancellationToken token)
{
    // Run blocking call on a thread, but respect cancellation
    var tcs = new TaskCompletionSource<Item>();
    using var reg = token.Register(() => tcs.TrySetCanceled(token));

    var workTask = Task.Run(() => tcs.TrySetResult(GetNextItem()));
    return await tcs.Task; // throws OperationCanceledException if cancelled
}
```

> ⚠️ This **abandons** the blocking thread — it doesn't kill it. This is the inherent cost of migrating away from `Thread.Abort`. True cooperative cancellation requires the blocking API itself to accept a token.
